data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` + `ResetAbort` | Control flow | Remove entirely |
| `new Thread(...)` + `Join(timeout)` | Manual threading | `Task.Run` + `WaitAsync` |

### Why It Breaks

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`). `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. The entire preemptive-abort model must be replaced with **cooperative cancellation**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw; // external cancellation — propagate as-is
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Changes Explained

1. **`CancellationTokenSource(timeout)`** — auto-cancels after the deadline, replacing `Join(timeout)` + `Abort()`
2. **`Task.Run` replaces `new Thread`** — uses the thread pool; avoids manual thread lifecycle
3. **`WaitAsync(token)`** — (.NET 6+) lets the *caller* stop waiting immediately on cancellation, even though the work may still be running briefly
4. **`OperationCanceledException` replaces `ThreadAbortException`** — the standard cooperative cancellation exception
5. **`using var cts`** — disposes the `CancellationTokenSource` to prevent timer leaks

### Critical Pitfall: Work Must Cooperate

`WaitAsync` unblocks the caller, but **the work delegate keeps running** until it checks the token. If `work` is a tight CPU loop or blocking I/O, it won't stop on its own. For full cooperation, pass the token into the work:

```csharp
// Caller passes token into work for true cooperative cancellation
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        cts.Token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---------|------------|
| `CancellationTokenSource` not disposed | Always `using`; leaks timers otherwise |
| Swallowing `OperationCanceledException` | Only catch at the top-level orchestration point |
| `Thread.Sleep` in the work delegate | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` — `Sleep` ignores the token |
| Truly uncooperative code (native/3rd-party) | Move to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` — only option in modern .NET |
